    "---\n",
    "## 10. Conclusion & Scientific Impact Statement\n",
    "\n",
    "This notebook demonstrates a novel **Physics-Informed Geo-AI** framework that connects high-dimensional satellite foundation models with mechanistic hydrological theory. By integrating **AlphaEarth satellite embeddings** with the **Inverse-SM2RAIN** soil-water balance equation, the framework produces scalable, physically constrained, high-resolution irrigation estimates across the California Central Valley.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Key Achievements\n",
    "\n",
    "| Achievement | Detail |\n",
    "|---|---|\n",
    "| **Physics-guided parameterization** | Deep learning infers soil-water parameters ($Z$, $K$, $b$) from satellite embeddings, creating a direct link between foundation model representations and hydrologic process behavior |\n",
    "| **Superior predictive accuracy** | Physics-Informed TabNet outperformed traditional numerical calibration with a **62.97% reduction in median MAE** and strong USGS benchmark agreement |\n",
    "| **Physically constrained outputs** | Multi-objective penalties (positivity, ET limits, precipitation masking, volumetric bounds) ensure all predictions are consistent with established hydrologic laws |\n",
    "| **Regional geospatial utility** | Irrigation estimates validated against USGS HUC-12 structures, demonstrating readiness for operational water accounting and groundwater sustainability applications |\n",
    "\n",
    "### Scientific Impact\n",
    "\n",
    "The broader contribution of this work is a **reproducible modeling strategy for integrating foundation model representations with mechanistic hydrology** — shifting satellite AI workflows away from purely empirical prediction and toward physically interpretable Earth system modeling. This framework serves as a bridge between modern Geo-AI and process-aware hydrologic science.\n",
    "\n",
